Let the initial minimum error in the measurement of the momentum be $\delta\_p$ and the initial minimum error in the measurement of the position be $\delta\_x$. According to Heisenberg's Uncertainty Principle, we have:
\begin{align*}
\delta\_p \cdot \delta\_x &\geq \frac{\pi}{8} \quad \text{(Equation 1)}
\end{align*}
Suppose the error in the measurement of the momentum of the particle is halved, so the new error in the measurement of the momentum is $\frac{\delta\_p}{2}$.
We want to find the new minimum error in the measurement of the position, denoted as $\delta\_x'$, in terms of the initial minimum error in the measurement of the position $\delta\_x$.
According to the Heisenberg's Uncertainty Principle with the halved momentum measurement, we have:
\begin{align*}
\left(\frac{\delta\_p}{2}\right) \cdot \delta\_x' &\geq \frac{\pi}{8} \quad \text{(Equation 2)}
\end{align*}
Now we need to solve for $\delta\_x'$, in terms of $\delta\_x$.
Dividing Equation 2 by $\delta\_x$, we get:
\begin{align*}
\frac{\delta\_p}{2\delta\_x} \cdot \delta\_x' &\geq \frac{\pi}{8} \quad \text{(Equation 3)}
\end{align*}
We can rewrite Equation 3 as:
\begin{align*}
\delta\_x' &\geq \frac{\pi \cdot 2\delta\_x}{8} \\
\delta\_x' &\geq \frac{\pi \cdot 2 \cdot \delta\_x }{8} \\
\delta\_x' &\geq \frac{\pi}{4} \cdot \delta\_x
\end{align*}
This means that the minimum error in the measurement of the position increases by at least $\frac{\pi}{4}$ compared to the initial minimum error in the measurement of the position $\delta\_x$.
